# Integrating Claude into Next.js with Streaming

The simplest approach is using the **Anthropic SDK** with Next.js API routes. Here's a complete setup:

## 1. Install Dependencies

```bash
npm install @anthropic-ai/sdk
```

## 2. Create an API Route

Create `pages/api/chat.ts`:

```typescript
import Anthropic from "@anthropic-ai/sdk";
import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from "next/server";

export const runtime = "nodejs";

export async function POST(req: NextRequest) {
  const { message, context } = await req.json();

  const client = new Anthropic();

  const stream = await client.messages.stream({
    model: "claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022",
    max_tokens: 1024,
    system: `You are a helpful assistant analyzing user data. 
    Context: ${context || "No context provided"}`,
    messages: [
      {
        role: "user",
        content: message,
      },
    ],
  });

  // Convert to ReadableStream for Next.js
  const readable = stream.toReadableStream();

  return new NextResponse(readable, {
    headers: {
      "Content-Type": "text/event-stream",
      "Cache-Control": "no-cache",
      Connection: "keep-alive",
    },
  });
}
```

## 3. Frontend Component

Create a React component to consume the stream:

```typescript
"use client";

import { useState, useRef } from "react";

export default function ChatComponent() {
  const [input, setInput] = useState("");
  const [response, setResponse] = useState("");
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);
  const abortRef = useRef<AbortController | null>(null);

  const handleSubmit = async (e: React.FormEvent) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    setLoading(true);
    setResponse("");
    abortRef.current = new AbortController();

    try {
      const res = await fetch("/api/chat", {
        method: "POST",
        headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
        body: JSON.stringify({
          message: input,
          context: "User's sales data for Q4 2024",
        }),
        signal: abortRef.current.signal,
      });

      if (!res.body) throw new Error("No response body");

      const reader = res.body.getReader();
      const decoder = new TextDecoder();

      while (true) {
        const { done, value } = await reader.read();
        if (done) break;

        const chunk = decoder.decode(value);
        // Parse Server-Sent Events format
        const lines = chunk.split("\n");

        for (const line of lines) {
          if (line.startsWith("data: ")) {
            const data = JSON.parse(line.slice(6));
            if (
              data.type === "content_block_delta" &&
              data.delta?.type === "text_delta"
            ) {
              setResponse((prev) => prev + (data.delta?.text || ""));
            }
          }
        }
      }
    } catch (error) {
      if (error instanceof Error && error.name !== "AbortError") {
        console.error("Chat error:", error);
      }
    } finally {
      setLoading(false);
    }
  };

  return (
    <div className="max-w-2xl mx-auto p-4">
      <form onSubmit={handleSubmit} className="space-y-4">
        <textarea
          value={input}
          onChange={(e) => setInput(e.target.value)}
          placeholder="Ask a question about your data..."
          className="w-full p-3 border rounded-lg"
          disabled={loading}
        />
        <button
          type="submit"
          disabled={loading}
          className="px-4 py-2 bg-blue-600 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-blue-700 disabled:opacity-50"
        >
          {loading ? "Streaming..." : "Ask"}
        </button>
      </form>

      {response && (
        <div className="mt-6 p-4 bg-gray-50 rounded-lg whitespace-pre-wrap">
          {response}
        </div>
      )}
    </div>
  );
}
```

## 4. Environment Setup

Add to `.env.local`:

```env
ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=your_key_here
```

## Key Points

- **Streaming** works via Server-Sent Events (SSE)
- **Real-time updates** appear as text arrives
- **Abort support** lets users cancel requests
- **Context injection** passes your user data to Claude
- Use `claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022` for best performance/cost balance

## Next Steps

- Add **conversation history** by storing messages in state or database
- Implement **rate limiting** on the API route
- Add **error handling** and user feedback
- Consider **caching** for repeated questions

This setup handles >95% of use cases. Scale to more complex scenarios only if needed.

# Prevent Unnecessary Re-renders in React

You have several options depending on your situation:

## 1. **React.memo** (Simplest for most cases)
Wraps your component to skip re-renders if props haven't changed:

```jsx
const MyComponent = React.memo(({ name, age }) => {
  console.log('Rendering...');
  return <div>{name} - {age}</div>;
});
```

**Note:** This does a shallow comparison of props. For complex objects/arrays, it won't work as expected.

## 2. **useMemo** (Memoize expensive computations)
```jsx
const MyComponent = ({ data }) => {
  const memoizedValue = useMemo(() => {
    return expensiveCalculation(data);
  }, [data]); // Only recalculate when 'data' changes

  return <div>{memoizedValue}</div>;
};
```

## 3. **useCallback** (Stable function references)
Prevent child components from re-rendering when you pass callback functions:

```jsx
const Parent = () => {
  const handleClick = useCallback(() => {
    // do something
  }, [dependency]); // dependencies array

  return <Child onClick={handleClick} />;
};
```

## 4. **Custom comparison with memo**
For complex props, define custom comparison logic:

```jsx
const MyComponent = React.memo(
  ({ user }) => <div>{user.name}</div>,
  (prevProps, nextProps) => {
    // Return true if props are equal (skip render)
    return prevProps.user.id === nextProps.user.id;
  }
);
```

## 5. **useMemo for object/array props** (Important!)
If your parent passes objects/arrays, they're recreated on each render:

```jsx
// ❌ Bad - new object created every render
<Child data={{ name: 'John' }} />

// ✅ Good - memoized object
const data = useMemo(() => ({ name: 'John' }), []);
<Child data={data} />
```

## Quick Decision Tree
- **Simple props** → `React.memo()`
- **Expensive calculations** → `useMemo()`
- **Callback functions** → `useCallback()`
- **Complex prop comparison** → Custom memo comparator

**Best practice:** Start simple with `React.memo()` and only optimize further if you identify actual performance issues.

# Recommended Architecture for Document Analysis Pipeline

For a small team processing 100-page PDFs, here's a practical approach that balances simplicity with capability:

## Core Architecture

**Single-pass analysis with structured outputs:**

1. **Upload PDF via Files API** → store file_id for reuse
2. **Claude Sonnet 4.6** (200K context) → analyze full PDF in one call
3. **Structured JSON output** → guaranteed schema for downstream use
4. **Optional knowledge base lookup** → lightweight integration if needed

This works because:
- 100-page PDFs fit comfortably in 200K context (PDFs typically use ~3-5 tokens/page, so ~300-500 tokens)
- Single pass = no chunking complexity, no context loss between sections, no orchestration overhead
- Files API enables reuse (avoid re-uploading the same PDF)
- Sonnet 4.6 is cost-effective for this workload

## Concrete Implementation

```python
import anthropic
import json

client = anthropic.Anthropic()

# 1. Upload PDF once, reuse file_id
def upload_pdf(file_path: str) -> str:
    with open(file_path, "rb") as f:
        response = client.beta.files.upload(
            file=(file_path.split("/")[-1], f, "application/pdf"),
        )
    return response.id

# 2. Analyze with structured output
def analyze_document(file_id: str, knowledge_base: dict = None) -> dict:
    kb_context = ""
    if knowledge_base:
        kb_context = f"""
You have access to this knowledge base:
{json.dumps(knowledge_base, indent=2)}

Cross-reference extracted information against it where relevant.
"""

    response = client.beta.messages.create(
        model="claude-sonnet-4-6",
        max_tokens=4096,
        messages=[
            {
                "role": "user",
                "content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": f"""Analyze this document and extract key information.

{kb_context}

Return a structured JSON with:
- summary: 2-3 sentence overview
- key_facts: list of important findings
- entities: names, dates, organizations mentioned
- cross_references: how it relates to known entities in the KB
- confidence: overall confidence level (high/medium/low)
- action_items: any next steps or decisions needed"""
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "document",
                        "source": {
                            "type": "file",
                            "file_id": file_id
                        }
                    }
                ]
            }
        ],
        output_config={
            "type": "json_schema",
            "schema": {
                "type": "object",
                "properties": {
                    "summary": {"type": "string"},
                    "key_facts": {
                        "type": "array",
                        "items": {"type": "string"}
                    },
                    "entities": {
                        "type": "object",
                        "properties": {
                            "people": {"type": "array", "items": {"type": "string"}},
                            "organizations": {"type": "array", "items": {"type": "string"}},
                            "dates": {"type": "array", "items": {"type": "string"}}
                        }
                    },
                    "cross_references": {
                        "type": "array",
                        "items": {
                            "type": "object",
                            "properties": {
                                "entity": {"type": "string"},
                                "kb_match": {"type": "string"},
                                "relevance": {"type": "string"}
                            }
                        }
                    },
                    "confidence": {"type": "string"},
                    "action_items": {"type": "array", "items": {"type": "string"}}
                },
                "required": ["summary", "key_facts", "entities"]
            }
        },
        betas=["files-api-2025-04-14"]
    )

    return json.loads(response.content[0].text)

# 3. Process pipeline
if __name__ == "__main__":
    file_id = upload_pdf("document.pdf")

    knowledge_base = {
        "known_partners": ["Acme Inc", "TechCorp"],
        "important_dates": ["2024-01-15", "2024-06-30"],
        "policies": ["compliance_v2", "data_retention"]
    }

    result = analyze_document(file_id, knowledge_base)
    print(json.dumps(result, indent=2))
```

## Why This Approach Works

| Aspect | Decision | Rationale |
|--------|----------|-----------|
| **Model** | Sonnet 4.6 | 200K context handles 100 pages, better cost/quality than Opus for this volume |
| **Chunking** | Single pass | No loss of context between pages, simpler code, cross-page relationships preserved |
| **Output format** | Structured JSON | Guaranteed schema → no parsing errors, easy downstream use, no hallucination risk |
| **Storage** | Files API | Reusable across analyses, persistent (ideal for team workflows) |
| **KB integration** | In-prompt | Simple for small KB (< 5K tokens), no extra round-trips |

## When to Scale/Adjust

**Add complexity only if:**
- **KB exceeds 10K tokens** → Store separately, use tool calls to fetch relevant context (`web_search_20260209` or custom MCP tool)
- **Need 50+ documents processed weekly** → Use Batch API (50% discount) for async overnight runs
- **Team wants to extract different schemas per document type** → Create reusable skills in Claude Code or Claude.ai Projects
- **Real-time streaming UI needed** → Add `stream: true` to the API call

## Cost Estimate
- **Per 100-page PDF**: ~500 tokens input (file) + 1,000 tokens output = $0.09 (Sonnet 4.6 at $3/$15 per MTok)
- **Files API overhead**: Negligible (included in usage)
- **100 documents/month**: ~$9

## For Your Small Team

**Immediate next steps:**
1. Set up a **Project on Claude.ai** or use **Claude Code** — build and test the extraction schema there first
2. Once schema is stable, move to the Python SDK for automation
3. Store results in a simple database (PostgreSQL, SQLite) keyed by file_id
4. Add a slash command in Claude Code (if using) to re-analyze with different prompts without re-uploading

This keeps things simple while staying production-ready. You can add sophistication (subagents for per-document type analysis, parallel processing) only when the current approach hits a bottleneck.

# QA System for AI-Generated Content

Here's a practical architecture that balances cost, latency, and quality:

## Recommended Pattern: Multi-Stage Pipeline

```
Input Content → Quick Filter → Deep Review → Compliance Check → Output
   (Haiku)      (Sonnet)       (Opus)         (Structured)
```

### Stage 1: Quick Filter (Haiku 4.5)
**Purpose**: Flag obvious issues early, reduce load on expensive models

```javascript
const quickFilter = await client.messages.create({
  model: "claude-3-5-haiku-20241022",
  max_tokens: 500,
  system: `You are a QA filter. Quickly identify critical issues:
- Factual errors or hallucinations
- Tone violations (too formal/casual)
- Missing required sections
- Formatting problems

Return PASS or list issues found.`,
  messages: [{
    role: "user",
    content: `Content to review:\n${content}`
  }]
});
```

**Cost**: ~$0.001 per review | **Speed**: <1s | Use for: Volume screening

### Stage 2: Deep Review (Sonnet 4.6 with adaptive thinking)
**Purpose**: Detailed accuracy and tone analysis for flagged content

```javascript
const deepReview = await client.messages.create({
  model: "claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022",
  max_tokens: 2000,
  thinking: { type: "adaptive" },  // Let Claude decide reasoning depth
  system: `You are a senior content QA reviewer. Analyze:

1. **Accuracy**: Verify factual claims against domain knowledge
2. **Tone**: Check alignment with brand voice
3. **Clarity**: Ensure logical flow and reader comprehension
4. **Compliance**: Verify against style guide (see attached)

Provide structured feedback with severity levels (critical/warning/info).`,
  messages: [{
    role: "user",
    content: content
  }]
});
```

**Cost**: ~$0.01-0.02 per review | **Speed**: 2-5s | Use for: Flagged or high-stakes content

### Stage 3: Structured Compliance Check (Sonnet with guaranteed JSON)
**Purpose**: Ensure consistent, machine-readable output

```javascript
const complianceCheck = await client.messages.create({
  model: "claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022",
  max_tokens: 1000,
  output_config: {
    type: "json_schema",
    schema: {
      type: "object",
      properties: {
        status: { enum: ["approved", "needs_revision", "rejected"] },
        issues: {
          type: "array",
          items: {
            type: "object",
            properties: {
              category: { enum: ["accuracy", "tone", "compliance", "clarity"] },
              severity: { enum: ["critical", "warning", "info"] },
              description: { type: "string" },
              location: { type: "string", description: "Sentence or section reference" },
              suggested_fix: { type: "string" }
            },
            required: ["category", "severity", "description"]
          }
        },
        approval_score: { type: "number", minimum: 0, maximum: 100 }
      },
      required: ["status", "issues", "approval_score"]
    }
  },
  system: `You are a compliance validator. Review content and output structured results.`,
  messages: [{ role: "user", content: content }]
});
```

**Cost**: ~$0.01 per review | **Speed**: 2-3s | Use for: All final reviews

---

## Full Implementation Pattern

```typescript
async function reviewContent(
  content: string,
  options: { tier: "fast" | "standard" | "thorough" } = { tier: "standard" }
): Promise<QAResult> {
  // Tier-based routing
  if (options.tier === "fast") {
    // Quick filter only (for time-sensitive content)
    const result = await quickFilter(content);
    return result.includes("PASS") ? { status: "approved" } : { status: "needs_revision" };
  }

  if (options.tier === "standard") {
    // Filter + structured compliance
    const filterResult = await quickFilter(content);

    if (filterResult.includes("PASS")) {
      return { status: "approved", confidence: "high" };
    }

    // Deep review on flagged content
    return await complianceCheck(content);
  }

  if (options.tier === "thorough") {
    // All three stages
    const filter = await quickFilter(content);
    const deep = await deepReview(content);
    const compliance = await complianceCheck(content);

    return {
      status: compliance.status,
      filterIssues: filter,
      deepAnalysis: deep,
      compliance: compliance,
      confidence: "very_high"
    };
  }
}
```

---

## Cost Optimization Strategies

### 1. **Use Prompt Caching for Style Guide**
```javascript
const systemPrompt = `You are a QA reviewer...

STYLE GUIDE:
${styleGuideContent}

[Keep this stable across requests]`;

const messages = [{
  role: "user",
  content: content,
  cache_control: { type: "ephemeral" }
}];

// After first request, subsequent calls reuse the cached style guide
// 10% discount on cached reads, 25% on writes
```

**Savings**: If your style guide is 2KB and you process 1000 items/day, caching pays for itself in ~3 hours.

### 2. **Batch API for Async Reviews**
```javascript
// Process 10,000 items at 50% discount
const batch = await client.beta.messages.batch.create({
  requests: contentItems.map(item => ({
    custom_id: item.id,
    params: {
      model: "claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022",
      max_tokens: 500,
      // ... review config
    }
  }))
});

// Check results after ~5 minutes
const results = await client.beta.messages.batch.retrieve(batch.id);
```

**When to use**: Overnight batch processing, scheduled daily reviews, non-urgent content

### 3. **Tiered Content Routing**
```
High-stakes (marketing, legal)  → Thorough (Opus + Sonnet)
Standard content                → Standard (Haiku + Sonnet)
Low-risk (internal comms)       → Fast (Haiku only)
```

---

## Architecture Decision: Subagents vs Tool Chaining

**Use tool chaining** (recommended for this case):
- All stages share context (~50K tokens)
- Single workflow, deterministic order
- Cost-effective (no isolation overhead)

```javascript
// Single conversation with sequential tool calls
const review = await client.messages.create({
  model: "claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022",
  tools: [
    { type: "code_execution", name: "run_filter" },
    { type: "code_execution", name: "run_compliance" }
  ],
  messages: [{ role: "user", content: `Review this content: ${content}` }]
});
```

**Use subagents only if**:
- Each stage needs different system prompts/tools (e.g., accuracy checker is separate expert)
- Stages run in parallel
- You need isolated rate limiting

---

## Production Checklist

- [ ] **Add human review queue** for "needs_revision" items — don't auto-reject
- [ ] **Track metrics**: approval rate by category, false positive rate
- [ ] **Version your style guide** — date it and log changes
- [ ] **Implement caching** — measure savings after 1 week
- [ ] **Rate limiting** — set quotas per content type
- [ ] **Fallback strategy** — what happens if API is down? (approve with flag + manual review)
- [ ] **Audit logging** — store original content + QA result for compliance
- [ ] **Test edge cases**: very long content (use Files API if >100K tokens), multiple languages, special characters

---

